Hi Terrell,

> As for Intel Macs, Apple is going EOL on Rosetta.=20

That is correct but not a relevant comment.   For the first time with =
v3.0.0 GA  we are providing a native build for Apple Silicon.  Why would =
anyone want to run an Intel version of WSJT-X on their Apple Silicon =
platform when a native ARM build is provided?

There is no logic in the suggestion that WSJT-X support should end for =
Intel Macs just because Rosetta on Apple Silicon will end.   There is a =
large WSJT-X Intel Mac community which is quite separate from Apple =
Silicon and support should (must) continue.  I recommend that your =
document should acknowledge this.

Apple Silicon requires that code for distribution should be signed (ant =
notarised) by someone (?) with a valid  Apple team account ($79 per =
annum).  Who might that person be?   (At the moment, that person is me.)

Your document requires this entitlement as part of code signing: =
com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory.  Apple suggests =
this is not a good idea.

=E2=80=94 John G4KLA=

