Sorry, it's been a hectic week, and will continue to be hectic until
probably the 20th.

This is really great, Terrel. The progress you've made toward automation is
simply fantastic. The docs are comprehensive and I'm assuming that they
can/will be updated as necessary; will they be living in a repo themselves?

A few questions/comments:
0) Which of these documents should be shared with potential external
contributors? Where do the documents live?
1) Hamlib - maybe a courtesy check to know whether there's a newer version
of hamlib than we're using of a particular hamlib series (e.g. warn if
4.8.0 is available when we're shipping against 4.7.0; not sure whether we
should mention v5 if we're using v4. Some versioning things (e.g. gemfiles)
use a nomenclature that specifies how to handle version checks).
2) mention "gh" is github CLI.
3) nice to haves include earlier base targets for mac 10.12 with x86 (or
universal?) AND later targets 15.x? for mac arm64
4) even if we're not using it, I *think* I recall we can built against qt6.
If we have an (optional) qt6 targeted build, we can understand when we
check in code not compatible with it
5) for the testing step, I think we'll be using ctest AND pfUnit to test
C++ code and Fortran code respectively. I think we can do that now!
6) when we do a source release, could we make that a target, too?

The last document - hygiene things we should be doing -- is really
important, I think we could resolve some issues per that document :-) and
then immediately file new ones to take care of some of those things :-).

-bkm

