Hi Terrell and all,

I've been busy with non-ham things most of today, but have now had time 
to read your five pdf docs. Your CI/CD pipeline is a *major* 
contribution to the WSJT project. I can't thank you enough for all the 
effort that went into it -- and for the clear way your documentation 
describes it for us. I can't wait to see it in action!

In no particular order, here are a few things that occurred to me as I 
read through your files.

  - It should be fairly easy to add some execution tests to add to the 
pipeline, especially after the effort Steve has already put into a 
script that tests the decoders for each of our supported modes.

  - We still use Qt5 so we can still support users with Windows 7. For 
the same reason, we probably want to maintain support for macOS 10.13 
and later on x86 hardware. Can those builds be added to the pipeline?

  - You made an excellent first cut at reasonable assignments of tasks 
and responsibilities. Group members should feel free to volunteer for 
other or additional tasks, and I will surely need to add Admin 
privileges to several others in our group.

  - Your scheme does not mention a way of dealing with "release 
candidates." We have used "-rc#" releases to let brave users experiment 
with and test new ideas. Should we keep such a capability? Or maybe 
handle it differently, in future?

  - About deploying your scheme for general use: I could grant full 
Admin privileges to Brian and Terrell, at least, and the two of you 
could bring it into a state for full use by all of us. You, Terrell, 
could surely do it quickest by yourself, but bringing Brian fully up to 
speed would also be advantageous. Does this approach make sense?

  - We have been planning to do a hotfix release of v3.0.1 soon, maybe 
even next week. Should we plan to use the pipeline for this purpose?

  - Right now, I believe wsjtx-internal/develop has JTTY code in it. So 
v3.0.1 should be based on wsjtx-internal/v3.0.0_test, rather 
than wsjtx-internal/develop.

  - Am I right that the contents of your pdf #4 would become the public 
file CONTRIBUTING.md ?

I'll probably have more thoughts/questions after thinking further on 
what you've sent us. I look forward to hearing what others think of it all!

     -- Joe

